  PART II: LINEAGE — WHAT ZAKO INHERITS

  - 2.1 From Unix: The Composable Small Tool
    - The Unix philosophy misremembered as CLI preference; actually an architecture doctrine
    - Small, independently auditable, loosely coupled components
    - ZAKO: Outstack is a daemon, not a feature; Telux services are separate processes
    - Graceful degradation in conditions where updates are infrequent and human support unavailable
  - 2.2 From Plan 9: The Namespace as Fundamental Primitive
    - Bell Labs, late 1980s: every resource is a file, every process has its own namespace
    - Plan 9 never achieved commercial success but ideas propagated (Linux namespaces → Docker → Kubernetes)
    - ZAKO's Island model: Plan 9's namespace doctrine applied to group exchange
    - Each Island is a constructed namespace, sovereign-defined, auditable by members, opaque to outsiders
  - 2.3 From seL4: The Capability as Unforgeable Token
    - Formally verified microkernel; mathematically proven correct
    - Capability tokens: unforgeable, delegatable, revocable
    - No ambient authority — no concept of "root" that can do everything
    - ZAKO: sovereignty as capability system — ed25519 keys backed by hardware, Island membership as signed capability grant
  - 2.4 From CICS: The Transaction as Substrate
    - IBM transaction monitors, COBOL, continuous operation since the 1960s
    - Millions of transactions per second across global banking
    - Survived 60 years because of the transaction model, not elegance
    - Every operation commits completely or rolls back, recorded before it executes, durable, reconstructible
    - ZAKO's exchange ledger aspires to this: not an application concern but an infrastructure property

