  PART III: THE FIVE FOUNDATIONAL PRINCIPLES

  - 3.1 Every Interaction Is a Record
    - Payment, task, blood pressure reading, capability grant, power mode transition, journal entry
    - Each is a BitPads frame, signed by Island Sovereign, chain-hashed against predecessor
    - Records never deleted — amended by new records that reference and supersede
    - Conservation principle: something happened → state changed → two sides → both recorded
  - 3.2 Conservation at the Wire Level
    - Every quantity record (money, energy, data, time) is a BitLedger record
    - Conservation invariant enforced at encoding — a batch that doesn't balance cannot be formed
    - Three independent error detection: CRC-15, cross-layer mirroring, conservation invariant
    - Not a rule the application must enforce — a structural property of the encoding
  - 3.3 Sovereignty Is the Design Constraint
    - Records not on external servers; identity not from third parties; data doesn't leave without explicit sovereign action
    - ed25519 keys backed by TrustZone hardware
    - W3C Decentralized Identifiers (did:key method)
    - Island containers with own security namespace and ledger
    - Capability grants as the mechanism for any cross-entity access
  - 3.4 Offline-First Is Non-Negotiable
    - Full function without network connectivity
    - Records created locally, stored locally, transmitted when Sovereign chooses
    - Four transmission channels: SMS (no data connection), QR code (no network at all), Bluetooth LE (short range, very low power), IP (when available)
  - 3.5 Power Is a Sovereignty Property
    - A device that cannot control power consumption cannot guarantee availability
    - Power events are records; power mode transitions are records; the power budget is a ledger
    - RTG-powered spacecraft discipline applied to terrestrial mobile devices

