  PART V: THE PROTOCOL FOUNDATION

  - 5.1 BitPads v2.0: The Meta Layer
    - Single meta byte declares frame type before receiver processes any payload
    - Four frame types spanning a cost spectrum from 1 byte to 44 bytes
    - Pure Signal (1 byte): heartbeat, daemon ACK, power alert
    - Anonymous Wave (4 bytes): sensor readings, pictography preamble
    - Full Record (13–29 bytes): work records, journal, health readings
    - Full BitLedger (22–44+ bytes): payments, exchanges, tallies, capability grants
  - 5.2 BitLedger v3.0: Conservation Enforced
    - 40-bit double-entry accounting record — five bytes encode any conserved scalar exchange
    - Conservation enforced at encoding time — structural property, not validation check
    - Universal Domain extension: same 40-bit record for energy, mass, data, time, service obligations
    - Domain declaration in session header — wire format identical, semantic interpretation changes
  - 5.3 The Enhancement Sub-Protocol
    - C0 Enhancement Grammar: reclaims structural bits in control characters
    - Priority, acknowledgement, continuation signalling at 13 declared positions
    - Binary pictography via shared codebooks at 4 bits per symbol
  - 5.4 The ZAKO Record Format
    - Address space: file_sep (0–7), record_sep (0–31), group_sep (0–62), sub_entity (0–31)
    - Sub-entity partitions: 0–7 Personal, 8–15 System, 16–31 Work
    - 64 task code verbs across domains (Exchange, Work, Health, Academy, Agreements, etc.)
    - Session headers, batch boundaries, BELL separators, Tally records
    - RESTRICT_FORWARD bit: one-bit sovereignty over record propagation
  - 5.5 The Wire Conventions
    - Separator encoding in BitLedger fields (account pair → separator, status bits → metadata)
    - Compound records spanning multiple frames with continuation
    - BELL before every Tally; Tally must be last in batch; compound cannot span BELL
    - Ledger storage mapping: SQLite schema for telux-ledgerd

