  PART VI: OUTSTACK — POWER AS ORGANIZING PRINCIPLE

  - 6.1 Not Power Management — Power Governance
    - Power management operates at margins; Outstack is the organizing principle of the entire runtime
    - Every process, service, Island, exchange operation understood in terms of power demands
    - Spacecraft discipline: RTGs, subsystem power budgets, graceful degradation
  - 6.2 The Five Modes
    - FULL (>80% or external power): unrestricted
    - NORMAL (60–80%): mild eDRX, extended sync intervals
    - CONSERVE (20–60%): lower-priority Islands suspended, display ceiling lowered
    - CRITICAL (5–20%): only CRITICAL and INTERACTIVE classes execute; deferred frozen not killed
    - EMERGENCY (<5%): survival posture, paging-only modem, state recorded to durable storage
    - Not user-selected profiles — operational states from objective measurement
  - 6.3 The Five Process Classes
    - CRITICAL: telux-ledgerd, telux-identd — never suspended
    - INTERACTIVE: user-facing, share daemon — responsive when active
    - BACKGROUND: sync, content prefetch, sensor daemon — deferred in conservation
    - DEFERRED: maintenance, cleanup — frozen in critical
    - OPPORTUNISTIC: learning engine — only when charging or >70%
  - 6.4 Execution Gating
    - At exec() time, Outstack checks power mode permits the process
    - In EMERGENCY, only CRITICAL-class processes execute
    - Not a firewall rule — a scheduling primitive
    - "A 10% battery is a device exercising sovereignty over which processes continue"
  - 6.5 Power Anomaly as Security Event
    - 2× budget for 60s → warning
    - System >20% above ceiling for 120s → anomaly event
    - Compromised peripheral can be physically power-killed — hardware power gating
    - Power state included in attestation reports
    - "A peripheral with no power has no attack surface — not policy, but physics"
  - 6.6 Thermal Override
    ▎ 45°C sustained 60s → EMERGENCY
    - Recovery requires <40°C sustained 120s
    - Temperature is a power event
  - 6.7 The Babb Cat Implementation
    - outstack-powerd daemon: five-mode state machine, 60s battery poll, netlink uevent subscription
    - cgroup hierarchy for power classes (CPU shares per mode, memory limits, freezer)
    - Process class assignment via xattr
    - Lid-close mode trigger: flip close → CONSERVE (form factor gains semantic meaning)
    - eDRX coordination: AT commands per mode (disabled → 5.12s → 10.24s → 20.48s → 40.96s)
    - Target: 8mA idle from 1450mAh = 72–108 hour standby

