  PART X: THE REFERENCE HARDWARE — BABB CAT

  - 10.1 The Device: Cat S22 Flip
    - Qualcomm QM215 (MSM8937): ARM Cortex-A53, 4 cores @ 1.4GHz, Adreno 308 GPU, 28nm
    - 2GB RAM, 16GB eMMC, 1450mAh battery
    - Flip form factor: 4" primary display + 1.44" cover display
    - Ruggedized: IP68, MIL-STD-810H
    - $99 device — a decade-old, well-documented SoC with vast community knowledge
  - 10.2 The Boot Chain
    - PBL (ROM, immutable) → SBL1 (initializes RAM, loads TrustZone) → RPM (power management microcontroller) → aboot/LK (fastboot, verified boot) → Linux kernel 4.9
    - Everything from aboot's payload onward is replaceable
    - PBL, SBL1, TrustZone trustlets are cryptographically locked — cannot be replaced
    - No UEFI ABL, no custom AVB key flash — orange state is the path
  - 10.3 The Vendor Blob Inventory
    - ~2,900 files in vendor partition
    - 56 firmware binaries, 27 HAL implementations
    - GPU kernel module + userspace EGL/GLES (no open alternative)
    - QMI modem driver (no open alternative)
    - Keymaster 4.0 TrustZone trustlet
    - Discovery: Awinic AW881xx smart amplifier firmware — not in any prior research
  - 10.4 The Partition Table
    - A-only (no seamless update slots)
    - Fixed partitions: sbl1, rpm, tz, aboot, boot (32MB), dtbo (8MB), vbmeta, recovery (32MB), userdata
    - Dynamic super partition (8.5GB): dm-linear volumes for system, vendor, product
    - "This one correct number — 32MB not 64MB — is worth significant time"
  - 10.5 The Cover Display and Lid Sensor
    - ST7789 SPI-connected cover display (1.44")
    - Hall effect lid sensor for flip detection
    - Flip close → CONSERVE power mode (form factor as sovereignty expression)
    - telux-coverd: time, date, battery bar, Outstack mode, ledger summary, caller ID
  - 10.6 The T9 Keypad
